The AI Shift, Increasing Returns, and Path Dependence
To understand how Rox might resolve this paradox, we need to understand som=
ething deeper about AI and timing.
AI is the Big Why Now, the platform shift that is launching a thousand star=
tups.=C2=A0
Apart from the fact that data is moving from Salesforce to data warehouses,=
 there is a broader once-in-a-Techno-Economic-Paradigm opportunity to build=
 new systems of record for two reasons:=C2=A0
Current AI Can Make Sense of Unstructured Data.
Companies Just Want to Buy AI. =C2=A0
Current AI Can Make Sense of Unstructured Data. Data was already moving fro=
m structured systems like Salesforce to unstructured data warehouses. Now, =
AI models can make sense of this chaos and deliver it in useful ways.=C2=A0
With the advantages of a structured database becoming less relevant, the st=
ructure is now a liability; it=E2=80=99s too heavy. It requires too much ma=
nual work from the user, when they could and should be doing more productiv=
e things.=C2=A0
Instead of taking a call and then manually entering notes into Salesforce, =
now you can just upload all of your emails, texts, and Gong calls and enter=
 it into a new system. Even with current models, a well-built system can ju=
st make sense of it all. Unstructured data is what AI does best.=C2=A0
Still, as we discussed, convincing companies to move to a new system is har=
d when they=E2=80=99ve invested so much money, time, and effort in the old =
one. How do you convince them to start uploading their emails, test, and Go=
ng calls into something new?=C2=A0
And I think the answer is as simple as: Companies Just Want to Buy AI.
This shows up in revenue numbers, earnings transcripts, everywhere. AI is t=
he hot new thing, and both consumers and companies are willing to spend to =
get it =E2=80=93 even if they=E2=80=99re just spending experimental budget,=
 at first. That experimental budget is a crack, a wedge, a small opening.
There is, right now, thanks to AI, an opportunity to sell products to compa=
nies that may otherwise have been happy sticking with their old software an=
d building internal tooling around it.=C2=A0
This rush to buy AI creates a couple of challenges, though.=C2=A0
First, revenue is easy but potentially not sticky, something I wrote about =
as far back as May 2023 in Small Applications, Growing Protocols [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/79442d3b-2492-4c93-b71f-770900decd64?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and expanded on in Whe=
n to Dig a Moat [ https://substack.com/redirect/dd37ebe2-1c80-4c04-8ea7-c70=
b3d8772af?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ].
This is why the VCs and commentariat are jumping up and down about the lack=
 of moats in generative AI. There is practically no uncertainty.=C2=A0
Second, while there is no uncertainty that AI is a big thing, there is a lo=
t of uncertainty about how models will improve =E2=80=93 that things are mo=
ving so fast =E2=80=93 that it feels like a leap of faith to bet on any one=
 application now. There are hundreds of Sales AIs in the market today.=C2=
=A0
Plus, it=E2=80=99s really hard to figure out which companies will win becau=
se the best product doesn=E2=80=99t always win and success is often depende=
nt on small, random events=E2=80=93on luck.=C2=A0
BUT, you have to compete now, because in these moments, cracks open that do=
n=E2=80=99t open often, and the companies that win =E2=80=93 whether or not=
 they have the best product today, whether or not they were just lucky, whe=
ther or not you build something better in the future =E2=80=93 get locked i=
n.=C2=A0
This dynamic - where early moves matter more than perfect execution - is ex=
actly what economist W. Brian Arthur explored in Increasing Returns and Pat=
h Dependence in the Economy [ https://substack.com/redirect/402a7013-be1d-4=
2b0-8203-111c96f47ca0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. In one key paper [ https://substack.com/redirect/16cf7d43-=
3221-49cf-8238-249fb3ac2162?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in the 1994 collection, he writes:=C2=A0
To the list of already known increasing-returns properties like potential i=
nefficiency and nonpredictability, a dynamic approach adds two new ones: in=
flexibility, in that allocations gradually rigidify, or lock-in, in structu=
re; and nonergodicity, in that small events early on may decide the larger =
course of structural change.
In English: early, small, and often random, events set a system on a path t=
hat self-reinforces and becomes hard to change. The outcomes at any given t=
ime are strongly influenced by the historical choices or events that led th=
ere.=C2=A0
Customers are sufficiently motivated by the AI hype today that they are wil=
ling to buy new tools. This creates a once-in-a-paradigm opportunity to get=
 into the core of customers=E2=80=99 workflows and become their system of r=
ecord. Once they make the switch and try something new, if it=E2=80=99s bet=
ter enough than what they=E2=80=99re using now, they might not switch again=
=2E The best product might not win. The=
 one that gets in the door, shows some=
 value, and becomes locked-in might.=C2=A0
In an environment like this, early strategy [ https://substack.com/redirect=
/0d21b79e-9a76-4408-b5f3-ef836f4ec406?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] matters a lot, because decisions today will=
 lock in winners for years to come.=C2=A0
You can=E2=80=99t afford to wait to build a product in a nascent market eve=
n if you think AI isn=E2=80=99t yet good enough to do everything that compa=
nies are promising it will.=C2=A0
So you need to play now, while the shift is happening, but the space is inc=
redibly competitive, full of companies overpromising based on what AI might=
 enable at some point in the future.=C2=A0
Arthur argues that luck plays a key role in determining the winner, but wha=
t struck me reading that book is that luck should be hackable. In other wor=
ds, companies should be able to make their own luck and pull the world onto=
 their path.
That is what Rox is doing, and it=E2=80=99s the best way to think about its=
