The Rox Strategy
How do you create path dependence?=C2=A0
Salesforce is the definition of path dependence: it=E2=80=99s not the best =
software, but it=E2=80=99s locked in.=C2=A0
The lesson from Salesforce is that you need to get customers to add integra=
tions and data to your system of record.=C2=A0
That is Rox=E2=80=99s goal, too.=C2=A0
Rox is a fuzzy acronym for Revenue Operating System. That is the long-term =
goal, to =E2=80=9Crun the world=E2=80=99s revenue.=E2=80=9D The official na=
me is Rox Data Corp. It was a data company before it was an AI company, and=
 data remains the most important thing.
=E2=80=9CFor us, AI is a means to an end,=E2=80=9D Ishan told me. =E2=80=9C=
My life is about using software and technology in a pragmatic context of dr=
iving productivity gains in the economy.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The company=E2=80=99s proximate goal is to build a new system of record for=
 revenue teams.=C2=A0
The way the company uses AI today is an implementation detail in service of=
 that proximate goal. How it will use AI in the future, when AI is stronger=
, will be a consequence of achieving that proximate goal.=C2=A0
The game right now is being useful enough, early enough to get customers to=
 connect their data.=C2=A0
This is how I=E2=80=99ve come to think about Rox=E2=80=99s strategy, and I =
think a version of it may be broadly applicable to all sorts of applied AI =
companies:=C2=A0
Get in the door with good enough AI. Rox uses today=E2=80=99s AI as a custo=
mer acquisition tool and as a way to be helpful enough to the best sellers =
at the best companies to get those companies to integrate all of the other =
tools and data they use to sell.=C2=A0
Build the System of Record. The data and integrations are the real prize in=
 the medium term. Use them to help customers build a unified system of reco=
rd that stays inside their own data structures and that they can manage. Be=
come an essential workflow.=C2=A0
Use That Position to Securely Train Agents. Over the long term, managing th=
e data and integrations - and becoming a part of companies=E2=80=99 workflo=
ws =E2=80=93 gives Rox the opportunity to securely train increasingly usefu=
l agents that can do more and more of the revenue teams=E2=80=99 functions =
as AI gets better and better.=C2=A0
Automate Revenue Operations. This is the huge prize: owning the agents that=
 work with the top 1% of salespeople and replace most of the rest.=C2=A0
In other words, use pretty good AI to acquire customers and embed in their =
workflow so that you=E2=80=99re best positioned to offer them increasingly =
powerful agents as models improve.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s break it down in more detail. Rox=E2=80=99s strategy starts w=
ith this premise:
AI is really good today but not great, and not nearly what it will be.=C2=
=A0
That sounds like an obvious premise, but it=E2=80=99s not consensus.
11x [ https://substack.com/redirect/8bb14cea-f5c4-4090-bddb-75666bf0845c?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which =
sells =E2=80=9CDigital Workers, Human Results for Sales, RevOps, and Go-To-=
Market Teams,=E2=80=9D just announced a $50 million Series B led a16z after=
 a $24 million Series A led by Benchmark in September.=C2=A0
The company=E2=80=99s manifesto [ https://substack.com/redirect/637fcacb-71=
79-429f-91a2-0573f2b3a0ac?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is the opposite of what Rox=E2=80=99s would be if they=
=E2=80=99d written one: =E2=80=9CWhile others offer tools that merely assis=
t human sales teams, 11x delivers complete revenue generation through auton=
omous AI workers that operate at scale.=E2=80=9D
That may be the right approach! I am not here to tell you that Rox is bette=
r than 11x or vice versa. The market will decide that. I=E2=80=99m here to =
learn, and analyze Rox=E2=80=99s strategy, and, to start at least, Rox=E2=
=80=99s strategy is to =E2=80=9Cmerely assist human sales teams.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0
Rox doesn=E2=80=99t want to replace people; it wants to make the best bette=
r.
Now that Rox has launched publicly, its website has more information than w=
hen I first encountered it. This is what it greets you with:=C2=A0
Rox is built to help the top sellers at the top companies =E2=80=93 Ramp, O=
penAI, and MongoDB are among Rox=E2=80=99s first customers =E2=80=93 do mor=
e of what they do best, the human side of selling that will probably never =
go away, the stuff you see on Mad Men.=C2=A0
Taken ad absurdum, in the future in which Rox succeeds, you can imagine one=
 incredibly talented seller supported by thousands of AI agents selling bil=
lions of dollars worth of business.=C2=A0
In this future, the pool of best sellers is shaped something like the NBA =
=E2=80=93 a few hundred of the obviously best, stratified even within that,=
 demanding eye-popping sums and earning their companies even more.=C2=A0
But that=E2=80=99s the future. We=E2=80=99ll get there.=C2=A0
Today, Rox offers companies swarms of agents =E2=80=93 one agent per accoun=
t, each tasked with knowing as much as possible about that single account b=
ased on internal and external information. With that information, it can al=
ert sellers in the right way at the right time, surface opportunities, and =
do things like helping to draft emails. It will not, for now, do the sellin=
g.=C2=A0
The idea is to make these agents so useful so quickly that companies add mo=
re integrations and data sources to make them even more useful, which gives=
 Rox the opportunity to cement itself in the workflow, build the system of =
record, and maybe, one day, topple Salesforce.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWhat takes a great seller 15-25 minutes of research on Google and =
LinkedIn, Rox accomplishes in one second,=E2=80=9D according to Max Freeman=
, the VP of Sales at Ramp. That saves time, makes his team more proactive, =
