The Rise of the Best=C2=A0
Another important piece of ensuring that your ambitions match your capabili=
ties, and to making your own luck, is to be targeted in your use of limited=
 resources.=C2=A0
Broadly speaking, Rox could have pursued three categories of customers:
Today=E2=80=99s Largest Companies.
Scaling Companies.=C2=A0
Small Startups.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Today=E2=80=99s Largest Companies don=E2=80=99t make sense for some of the =
reasons we=E2=80=99ve already discussed. They=E2=80=99re probably not build=
ing their own products on top of the data warehouse, may not have the urgen=
cy of a smaller company, and are likely to die with their Salesforce boots =
on.
The third approach - Small Startups =E2=80=93 is almost the default for sta=
rtups thanks to Stripe=E2=80=99s success getting in with developers early a=
nd growing with them. That that approach worked for Stripe, though, was due=
 to a much more specific reason than most people realize: SMBs were a perfe=
ct first customer because, with lower spend volumes, they weren=E2=80=99t a=
s sensitive to take rates as Adyen=E2=80=99s larger customers, which meant =
Stripe has always had a higher average take rate.=C2=A0
In Rox=E2=80=99s case, small companies aren=E2=80=99t the right target: the=
y probably don=E2=80=99t have a real sales org yet, nor do they yet have th=
e best salespeople.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CYou want to raise the ceiling of what someone incredible can do ve=
rsus raise the floor on what a shitty salesperson at a small company can do=
,=E2=80=9D as one person colorfully put it.=C2=A0
Instead of taking Stripe=E2=80=99s approach, Rox is targeting companies lik=
e Stripe itself: tech-forward enterprises with enough scale that Rox matter=
s.=C2=A0
Smaller organizations can, in the famous words of YCombinator, =E2=80=9CDo =
things that don=E2=80=99t scale.=E2=80=9D Scaling companies definitionally =
need to do things that can.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWe have deep founder-market fit in businesses at scale,=E2=80=9D I=
shan explained, =E2=80=9Cbusinesses doing $100M or even $1 billion in reven=
ue. We want to become essential, which happens at a certain number of reps =
and revenue.=E2=80=9D
Ishan calls their approach selling to these companies =E2=80=9CPalantir-sty=
le=E2=80=9D: =E2=80=9CWe want to help business owners when they=E2=80=99re =
in extreme pain or when there=E2=80=99s extreme priority.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
In the beginning, like Palantir, that also means getting to work closely wi=
th the best people at the best companies to develop the product, another be=
nefit to the focus on the best.=C2=A0
Kiran at Ramp said that Rox co-founder Diogo Ribeiro has been building alon=
gside her since Ramp started using Rox. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s flying out to=
 NYC for the team=E2=80=99s offsite next week,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9C=
He already did that once a month ago.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
If the long game is to collect the data =E2=80=93 not just the moment in ti=
me data, but an ongoing understanding of the way that the best sellers thin=
k and operate =E2=80=93 in order to train better models for revenue teams, =
there=E2=80=99s no substitute for working with the best. Gold in, gold out.=
=C2=A0
The other half of working with the best is working with and for the best se=
llers inside the best companies.=C2=A0
Speaking with Ishan, Kiran, Max, and others around the company it was hard =
not to get the sense that AI tools =E2=80=93 Rox specifically, but more gen=
erally, too =E2=80=93 will 1000x the capabilities of the top people and rep=
lace mediocre ones.=C2=A0
Max put it bluntly:=C2=A0
This may sound ruthless, but if you=E2=80=99re a mediocre seller or worse, =
your job is over. You=E2=80=99re truly done. If you=E2=80=99re better than =
mediocre, you=E2=80=99re becoming a lot more efficient. You can focus on se=
