But the metrics never do justice to the je ne sais quoi that you get from a=
 company that just ships really fast against a really high quality bar. Rox=
 has the je ne sais quoi.=C2=A0
Every time I interview people for a deep dive, I ask, =E2=80=9CIf you read =
this piece and it=E2=80=99s missing X, you=E2=80=99ll be like =E2=80=98Man,=
 he missed the point.=E2=80=99 What=E2=80=99s X?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Kiran said that two things stick out with Rox: Empathy - deeply understandi=
ng customer needs =E2=80=93 and Speed of Execution.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CA lot of people are trying to fix the same problems,=E2=80=9D she =
said. =E2=80=9CBeing first doesn=E2=80=99t always matter. Velocity and spee=
d of execution can overcome that.=E2=80=9D I swear I didn=E2=80=99t tell he=
r about the Path Dependence thesis.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CSeeing someone shipping at that velocity Ramp did, interacting in =
the same way Ramp did with customers,=E2=80=9D she added. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=
=99s Ramp=E2=80=99s playbook.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The playbook is actually fairly simple, if hard to execute: get insanely sm=
art people who work obsessively hard on a hard problem in a big market poin=
ted in the right direction for the future.
Ishan credits the small size and high caliber of the team with the company=
=E2=80=99s velocity. He buckets the 14-person team into three categories (a=
ll engineers, for now, to sell without a large sales team, Rox=E2=80=99s fo=
under use Rox):=C2=A0
Backend data people: Shriram Sridharan is Rox=E2=80=99s CTO and co-founder.=
 Before Rox, he led the data infrastructure team at Confluent responsible f=
or making Kafka [ https://substack.com/redirect/fa23f92e-2611-4113-bce2-4c7=
ccd90077c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNp=
U ] faster and cheaper across clouds, and before that, he was a pre-launch =
engineer at Amazon Aurora, =E2=80=9Cre-imagining databases for the cloud.=
=E2=80=9D He works with Lawrence Li, an International Olympiad of Informati=
cs Gold medalist [ https://substack.com/redirect/0b9ca396-9ca3-484d-a8ef-68=
237d5c6000?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ].
Applied AI: Top Stanford AI folks, led by co-founder Avanika Narayan, a Sta=
nford Tennis player and Knight-Hennessy Scholar who [ https://substack.com/=
redirect/15ecb427-13a4-4e20-aeeb-4146fbe0af6d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=9Cdrew from her PhD research=
 applying LLMs to enterprise tasks like data wrangling and workflow automat=
ion.=E2=80=9D
Full-Stack Engineers: Ishan simply calls them =E2=80=9Cinsane humans who we=
re or will be founders.=E2=80=9D One, Yuma Tanaka [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/2397da13-440c-4b8e-8e0e-d97468354e4a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], reportedly pulled two all-nighters i=
n a row. Another sent the company a Slack message at 2pm on a Sunday tellin=
g them that he was going to meet up with a friend for lunch but that he=E2=
=80=99d be back in the office shortly.=C2=A0
There are echoes of Ramp here, too =E2=80=93 the international intelligence=
 gold medalists, AI savants, and former and future founders. More than pedi=
gree, though, there=E2=80=99s something about a small team of people at the=
 top of their game executing rapidly and responsively with customers that=
=E2=80=99s hard to describe but obvious to observe. Rox has it.=C2=A0
That kind of team is insanely productive. It=E2=80=99s the kind of team tha=
t Rox is today, and wants to help more of the best companies become and rem=
ain in the future.=C2=A0
The Future of the Free Market=C2=A0
I knew I liked Ishan pretty quickly once I started talking to him, but I re=
ally knew when he described himself as an =E2=80=9Cowner/operator/capitalis=
t,=E2=80=9D and said this:=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CMy life is about driving productivity in the free market.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0
He had, he told me, =E2=80=9Ca visceral understanding of the impact of tech=
nology on humans.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
When New Relic acquired his startup, Pixie, he ran product before realizing=
 that if he wanted to change the company=E2=80=99s fortunes, he=E2=80=99d h=
ave to change how it sold. He became Chief Revenue Officer.=C2=A0
When he took over, the company was doing $800 million in subscription reven=
ue. But he saw the writing on the wall for subscription-based businesses, s=
o he drove that business to zero while building up a $1 billion consumption=
-based business, as a public company, during COVID.=C2=A0
As part of the transformation, he took his team from 1,600 people to 600 pe=
ople=E2=80=A6 and grew sales by 30%. He earned a lesson: =E2=80=9CThere are=
 a lot of folks who unfortunately need to be reskilled or are not critical.=
 You can make the best quota-carrying people more productive, and then empl=
oy fewer people.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Harsh truth, but if your goal is to drive productivity in the free market, =
an important one.=C2=A0
The Acquired guys are fond of saying [ https://substack.com/redirect/226e0a=
60-2f27-433f-adda-9789e9da5e56?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that =E2=80=9Ccompanies are just founders extended=
=E2=80=A6 It=E2=80=99s very hard for me to point to a truly great company w=
here the DNA isn=E2=80=99t like a lever on the founder=E2=80=99s personalit=
y.=E2=80=9D
While it=E2=80=99s early in Rox=E2=80=99s journey, it=E2=80=99s clear that =
Rox is Ishan extended, and Rox is a leveraged way for Ishan to drive produc=
tivity in the free market. So understanding Ishan=E2=80=99s vision is instr=
uctive in determining what the future might look like if Rox succeeds.=C2=
=A0
To that end, there=E2=80=99s another 40% stat that I=E2=80=99ve been saving=
=2E When we first spoke, Ishan point=
ed out that =E2=80=9C40% of business spen=
d is GTM.=E2=80=9D It is a huge chunk of the global economy.=C2=A0
Rhetorically, he asked, =E2=80=9CCan they be 5-10% more efficient? Can we r=
eturn 5-10% savings to the CEO and the CEO.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Confidently, he answered, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve done that, twice, at scale,=
 without a fully built-out system like Rox.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
With Rox, he thinks, the efficiency gains will be more dramatic. Smaller te=
ams, more revenue, higher margins. Grunt work: eliminated. Human touch: ele=
vated.=C2=A0
This is where I started asking him questions like, =E2=80=9CWhat are we all=
 going to do with ourselves in the future?=E2=80=9D And, =E2=80=9CWill all =
sales just be bot-to-bot.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Some of it will be, he thinks, but there will be human winners, those with =
the =E2=80=9Ccreative force.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CMost businesses have a few people coming up with change and drivin=
g it,=E2=80=9D he says. =E2=80=9CThey will get more and more empowered.=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0
Within revenue teams specifically, he plans to drive this empowerment with =
Rox.=C2=A0
As we=E2=80=99ve discussed, the proximate goal right now, while AI isn=E2=
=80=99t that good yet, is just to earn the data and integrations, to become=
 the system of record. Over the next year, he wants to save sellers 20 to 3=
0 hours every week while making them 50% more effective.=C2=A0
But that=E2=80=99s not the ultimate goal.=C2=A0
The ultimate goal is to use that data to train models on what and how the b=
est companies at the best sellers sell in order to deliver full automation,=
 when the time is right, for the things that the best humans don=E2=80=99t =
need to do so that they have the tools and resources to amplify what they d=
o best.=C2=A0=C2=A0
The models aren=E2=80=99t there yet, but they=E2=80=99ll get there. Everyth=
ing other than building relationships and educating customers =E2=80=93 the=
 non-human stuff =E2=80=93 will mostly be delivered by agents.
The opportunity for Rox is building the best team and best product with tec=
h-forward customers to own the application layer for this as underlying mod=
els get good enough to fulfill the grand promises companies are making abou=
t their capabilities today.=C2=A0
This is another update to my mental model of AI: even as the foundation mod=
els themselves get smarter, there=E2=80=99s reason to believe that there wi=
ll be a ton of value in the application layer.
Intelligence doesn=E2=80=99t equal usefulness. Here=E2=80=99s a thought exe=
rcise that one of Rox=E2=80=99s investors put to me:=C2=A0
If you hired a 160 IQ college grad, they wouldn=E2=80=99t be able to do muc=
h on Day 1. If you spent a year training them, they could probably start do=
ing good things. That=E2=80=99s what the application layer is: guiding supe=
r intelligent models to work in context. The broad opportunity at the appli=
cation layer is building the data and workflows to make AI useful.
Even in my first conversation with Ishan, I was convinced Rox had what it t=
akes to win, that by playing the long game, it could build the data and wor=
kflows to make AI useful to sellers.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s why I kept asking if he had a hard stop, so I could flood hi=
m with questions about the future he saw so clearly, the one that he=E2=80=
=99s working to bring about.=C2=A0
One category of questions was, essentially, if everyone uses Rox, is there =
any alpha in Rox?=C2=A0
If every company had access to really smart, really useful sales agents, wo=
uldn=E2=80=99t the advantage disappear?=C2=A0
Wouldn=E2=80=99t the customers just get hit with the same perfectly targete=
d messages at the same perfect time?=C2=A0
Wouldn=E2=80=99t customers just be overwhelmed with equally good messages a=
nd ignore all of them?
Would all sales just be bots selling to bots based on product specs? Wouldn=
=E2=80=99t developer agents working with sales agents just build solutions =
tailored to those specs?=C2=A0
What are us humans going to do with ourselves when the AI takes our jobs?=
=C2=A0
Pulling me out of my existential tailspin, Ishan told me he believes that t=
here will inevitably be winners and losers.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThe alpha will be an arbitrage on information: what information yo=
u have about your customers and how proactive you are in using it,=E2=80=9D=
 he explained.=C2=A0
Information is half the battle =E2=80=93 the best companies will have more =
and better customers, so they=E2=80=99ll have more and better information, =
and their advantage will compound.=C2=A0
The other half is what you do with it. For that, the human element remains.
=E2=80=9CNon-killers are going to go away,=E2=80=9D he predicts, =E2=80=9Ca=
nd killers are going to be supercharged. It=E2=80=99s the same with compani=
es: I do believe that there is a class of companies that will not survive.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
What will those companies look like?=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CYou need to judge by the person driving the bus.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The world in which Rox succeeds is not a world in which humans disappear. I=
t is a world in which humans are amplified, for better or worse.=C2=A0
Rox will succeed because Ishan and the small, exceptional team he=E2=80=99s=
 built will wield agents to amplify their human strengths.=C2=A0
The Acquired framing is useful here: companies are just founders extended. =
Great companies are force multipliers on their founders=E2=80=99 vision and=
 capabilities.=C2=A0
With tools like Rox, everyone will be extended. Agents will be force multip=
liers on your vision and capabilities.=C2=A0
What became clear to me early in my conversations with Ishan is that Rox is=
 a master class in Applied AI strategy: how to manufacture path dependence =
by taking the long view and matching current capabilities to future aspirat=
ions.=C2=A0
What=E2=80=99s become clear to me writing this piece is that those same les=
sons might apply to people, too.=C2=A0
A world full of highly capable agents is coming. The best will get better. =
But you know it=E2=80=99s coming. You can make your own luck if you take th=
e long view and double-down on your unique capabilities today in anticipati=
on of their future amplification.=C2=A0
Pretty heady stuff for a piece on boring CRM software!
Thanks to Claude for editing and to Ishan, Eric, Max, Kiran, and everyone e=
lse who shared their insights for this piece!=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today. Have a great Thanksgiving. We=E2=80=99ll be b=
ack in your inbox with a Weekly Dose on Friday.=20
Thanks for reading,
Packy

