p;</strong></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-h=
eight: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>This is the paradox at the heart of </s=
pan><em>every </em><span>applied AI company. So it&#8217;s worth diving eve=
n deeper here before we answer how Rox plans to resolve it.&nbsp;</span></p=
><h3 class=3D"header-anchor-post" style=3D"position: relative;--highlight-b=
g: rgba(var(--color-bg-accent-themed-rgb), 0.2);font-family: 'SF Pro Displa=
y', -apple-system-headline, system-ui, -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, '=
Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Sego=
e UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol';font-weight: bold;-webkit-font-smoothing: an=
tialiased;-moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased;-webkit-appearance: optimize=
legibility;-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility;appearance: optimizelegibili=
ty;margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 1.16em;font-=
size: 1.375em;"><strong>The AI Shift, Increasing Returns, and Path Dependen=
ce</strong></h3><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-=
height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">To understand how Rox might resolve this par=
adox, we need to understand something deeper about AI and timing.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size=
: 16px;">AI is the Big Why Now, the platform shift that is launching a thou=
sand startups.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 5=
5);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Apart from the fact that data is mov=
ing from Salesforce to data warehouses, there is a broader once-in-a-Techno=
-Economic-Paradigm opportunity to build new systems of record for two reaso=
ns:&nbsp;</p><ol style=3D"margin-top: 0;padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8=
px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;margin-b=
ottom: 0;box-sizing: border-box;padding-left: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0=
;"><strong>Current AI Can Make Sense of Unstructured Data.</strong></p></li=
><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55);lin=
e-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing: border-box;padding-left: 4px;fo=
nt-size: 16px;margin: 0;"><strong>Companies Just Want to Buy AI. &nbsp;</st=
rong></p></li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);li=
ne-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><strong>Current AI Can Make Sense of Unst=
ructured Data. </strong><span>Data was already moving from structured syste=
ms like Salesforce to unstructured data warehouses. Now, AI models can make=
 sense of this chaos and deliver it in useful ways.&nbsp;</span></p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size:=
 16px;">With the advantages of a structured database becoming less relevant=
, the structure is now a liability; it&#8217;s too heavy. It requires too m=
uch manual work from the user, when they could and should be doing more pro=
ductive things.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, =
55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Instead of taking a call and then m=
anually entering notes into Salesforce, now you can just upload all of your=
 emails, texts, and Gong calls and enter it into a new system. Even with cu=
rrent models, a well-built system can just make sense of it all. Unstructur=
ed data is what AI does best.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color=
: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Still, as we discusse=
d, convincing companies to move to a new system is hard when they&#8217;ve =
invested so much money, time, and effort in the old one. How do you convinc=
e them to start uploading their emails, test, and Gong calls into something=
 new?&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-h=
eight: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>And I think the answer is as simple as:=
 </span><strong>Companies Just Want to Buy AI.</strong></p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">T=
his shows up in revenue numbers, earnings transcripts, everywhere. AI is th=
e hot new thing, and both consumers and companies are willing to spend to g=
et it &#8211; even if they&#8217;re just spending experimental budget, at f=
irst. That experimental budget is a crack, a wedge, a small opening.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-s=
ize: 16px;">There is, right now, thanks to AI, an opportunity to sell produ=
cts to companies that may otherwise have been happy sticking with their old=
 software and building internal tooling around it.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">=
This rush to buy AI creates a couple of challenges, though.&nbsp;</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size=
: 16px;"><span>First, revenue is easy but potentially not sticky, something=
 I wrote about as far back as May 2023 in </span><em><a href=3D"https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/79442d3b-2492-4c93-b71f-770900decd64?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: r=
gb(54, 55, 55);text-decoration: underline;">Small Applications, Growing Pro=
tocols</a></em><span> and expanded on in </span><em><a href=3D"https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/dd37ebe2-1c80-4c04-8ea7-c70b3d8772af?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: rg=
b(54, 55, 55);text-decoration: underline;">When to Dig a Moat</a></em><span=
>.</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #0c2427;margin: 20=
px 0;padding: 0;"><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);mar=
gin-left: 20px;line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><em><span>This is why th=
e VCs and commentariat are jumping up and down about the lack of moats in g=
enerative AI. </span><strong>There is practically no uncertainty</strong><s=
pan>.&nbsp;</span></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;colo=
r: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Second, while there =
is no uncertainty that AI is a big thing, there is a lot of uncertainty abo=
ut how models will improve &#8211; that things are moving so fast &#8211; t=
hat it feels like a leap of faith to bet on any one application now. There =
are hundreds of Sales AIs in the market today.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><spa=
n>Plus, it&#8217;s really hard to figure out </span><em>which </em><span>co=
mpanies will win because the best product doesn&#8217;t always win and succ=
ess is often dependent on small, random events&#8211;on luck.&nbsp;</span><=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;=
font-size: 16px;">BUT, you have to compete now, because in these moments, c=
racks open that don&#8217;t open often, and the companies that win &#8211; =
whether or not they have the best product today, whether or not they were j=
ust lucky, whether or not you build something better in the future &#8211; =
get locked in.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 5=
5);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>This dynamic - where early mov=
es matter more than perfect execution - is exactly what economist W. Brian =
Arthur explored in </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/402a=
7013-be1d-42b0-8203-111c96f47ca0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55);text-dec=
oration: underline;">Increasing Returns and Path Dependence in the Economy<=
/a></em><span>. In </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/16cf7d43=
-3221-49cf-8238-249fb3ac2162?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55);text-decorat=
ion: underline;">one key paper</a><span> in the 1994 collection, he writes:=
&nbsp;</span></p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #0c2427;margin=
: 20px 0;padding: 0;"><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55)=
;margin-left: 20px;line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><em><span>To the lis=
t of already known increasing-returns properties like </span><strong>potent=
ial inefficiency</strong><span> and </span><strong>nonpredictability</stron=
g><span>, a dynamic approach adds two new ones: </span><strong>inflexibilit=
y</strong><span>, in that allocations gradually rigidify, or lock-in, in st=
ructure; and </span><strong>nonergodicity</strong><span>, in that small eve=
nts early on may decide the larger course of structural change.</span></em>=
</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line=
-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">In English: early, small, and often random,=
 events set a system on a path that self-reinforces and becomes hard to cha=
nge. The outcomes at any given time are strongly influenced by the historic=
al choices or events that led there.&nbsp;</p><div class=3D"captioned-image=
