></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26p=
x;font-size: 16px;">Taken ad absurdum, in the future in which Rox succeeds,=
 you can imagine one incredibly talented seller supported by thousands of A=
I agents selling billions of dollars worth of business.&nbsp;</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: =
16px;">In this future, the pool of best sellers is shaped something like th=
e NBA &#8211; a few hundred of the obviously best, stratified even within t=
hat, demanding eye-popping sums and earning their companies even more.&nbsp=
;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26p=
x;font-size: 16px;">But that&#8217;s the future. We&#8217;ll get there.&nbs=
p;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26=
px;font-size: 16px;"><span>Today, Rox offers companies </span><strong>swarm=
s of agents</strong><span> &#8211; one agent per account, each tasked with =
knowing as much as possible about that single account based on internal and=
 external information. With that information, it can alert sellers in the r=
ight way at the right time, surface opportunities, and do things like helpi=
ng to draft emails. It will not, for now, do the selling.&nbsp;</span></p><=
p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font=
-size: 16px;">The idea is to make these agents so useful so quickly that co=
mpanies add more integrations and data sources to make them even more usefu=
l, which gives Rox the opportunity to cement itself in the workflow, build =
the system of record, and maybe, one day, topple Salesforce.&nbsp;</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-siz=
e: 16px;">&#8220;What takes a great seller 15-25 minutes of research on Goo=
gle and LinkedIn, Rox accomplishes in one second,&#8221; according to Max F=
reeman, the VP of Sales at Ramp. That saves time, makes his team more proac=
tive, and helps the sellers sell.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;c=
olor: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Rox contractually=
 obligates itself to provide value out of the gate. The company writes its =
contracts such that if customers don&#8217;t get a 2x ROI on Rox in the fir=
st 90 days, they can cancel. Today, customers make their money back on new =
opportunities created, at-risk customers saved, and growth from high-potent=
ial customers.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 5=
5);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">If Rox does what it says it does, th=
e company is betting that people will feed it more data and integrations so=
 that it can make them even more efficient.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 =
0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">But a 9=
-figure valuation for a one-year-old company suggests investors see somethi=
ng beyond mere efficiency gains.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;co=
lor: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>I think it&#=
8217;s this: </span><strong>Rox is using the fact that companies are willin=
g to buy AI as a foot in the door to prove usefulness to get more data and =
integrations to build the system of record and earn customer trust and usag=
e and learn so that Rox is ready when AI gets really good.</strong></p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-si=
ze: 16px;"><span>This isn&#8217;t just good strategy, it&#8217;s </span><em=
>grand</em><span> strategy.&nbsp;</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>In </span>=
<em><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/9c78431b-2e54-4469-8e60-b3d520=
aca0d6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" =
rel=3D"" style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55);text-decoration: underline;">On Gr=
and Strategy</a><span>, </span></em><span>John Lewis Gaddis defines the ter=
m as &#8220;the alignment of potentially unlimited aspirations with necessa=
rily limited capabilities.&#8221;</span></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Grand strategy r=
equires an honest assessment of those limited capabilities as they are toda=
y, not as you want them to be.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;colo=
r: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">&#8220;Napoleon lost=
 his empire by confusing aspirations with capabilities; Lincoln saved his c=
ountry by not doing so.&#8221;&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;colo=
r: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">In Rox&#8217;s case,=
 the capabilities of AI agents as they stand today are that they:</p><ol st=
yle=3D"margin-top: 0;padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p st=
yle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing=
: border-box;padding-left: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;">Can make sense o=
f unstructured data.</p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;margin-bottom: 0;box-sizing: b=
order-box;padding-left: 4px;font-size: 16px;margin: 0;">Are excellent custo=
mer acquisition tools.&nbsp;</p></li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;co=
lor: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Today, in other wo=
rds, AI is a means, not an end. A capability, not an aspiration.&nbsp;</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font=
-size: 16px;"><span>Rox&#8217;s approach, as Ishan described it, is to </sp=
an><strong>&#8220;build whatever you need to build to get companies to feed=
 your system of record.&#8221;&nbsp;</strong></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Instead of =
promising agents that will sell for you, they build agents that will help y=
ou sell.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);lin=
e-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">Instead of helping sellers go after new cu=
stomers, Rox helps them &#8220;go after the most unglamorous piece &#8211; =
their existing customers.&#8221; This, Ishan tells me, is who &#8220;80-90%=
 of revenue comes from.&#8221; It&#8217;s also who companies have the most =
data on. And it&#8217;s the group of companies worst-served by existing sys=
tems, which are focused on contract-based versus consumption-based sales.&n=
bsp;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: =
26px;font-size: 16px;">This approach addresses the two big concerns I&#8217=
;ve had about AI application companies, turns them into advantages, even.&n=
bsp;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: =
26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>&#8220;First, revenue is easy but potentially =
not sticky, something I wrote about as far back as May 2023 in </span><em><=
a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/79442d3b-2492-4c93-b71f-770900decd6=
4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=
=3D"" style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55);text-decoration: underline;">Small Ap=
plications, Growing Protocols</a></em><span>.&#8221;</span></p><p style=3D"=
margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px=
;">In Rox&#8217;s case, AI support agents are the small applications, and t=
he data and workflows are the company&#8217;s own &#8220;protocol&#8221; wh=
ich gets more valuable with time, integrations, and more applications from =
Rox itself. Like a protocol, it is open &#8211; companies will build on Rox=
 if it&#8217;s the best place to build, and leave and take their data with =
them if it isn&#8217;t.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(=
54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">&#8220;Second, there is so =
much uncertainty about how models will improve &#8211; that things are movi=
ng so fast &#8211; that it feels like a leap of faith to bet on any one app=
lication now. There are dozens, if not hundreds, of GTM AIs in the market t=
oday,&#8221; including well-funded ones like 11x.</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 =
0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;"><span>P=
roving value early and often, incrementally at first, is a way to </span><e=
m>manufacture</em><span> increasing returns and path dependence.&nbsp;</spa=
n></p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;color: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26=
px;font-size: 16px;">Small early wins at high velocity compound. Overpromis=
ing and underdelivering does not.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"margin: 0 0 20px 0;c=
olor: rgb(54, 55, 55);line-height: 26px;font-size: 16px;">So what does Rox =
promise, and do, today?&nbsp;</p><h3 class=3D"header-anchor-post" style=3D"=
